<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-548-770  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 548 770.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  May 1990 v27 n5 p62(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Linking LANS with X.25 gateways. (local area networks )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Luczak, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Remote users must have access to a local area network(LAN)-connected host to achieve the goal of total connectivity.andO;Connecting a remote terminal across a wide area network (WAN) to ahost on a LAN can be complicated.andP;  Steps to do this include makinga cost-effective connection between the remote site and the hostand making sure that a link, once it is established, can be usedby remote users to access hosts on the LAN.andP;  Communicationsbetween the host and the remote users should be as transparent aspossible.andP;  X.25, a WAN standard for remote access to hosts, shouldbe considered.andP;  A packet-switching interface installed in a hostprocessor can connect the LAN to the X.25 network.andP;  Another methodis to use a stand-alone X.25 server/gateway.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Wide Area NetworksX.25 ProtocolLocal Area NetworksPacket Switching.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>